04897nam a22007695i 9780804798983DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2015045652  a97808047989837 a10.1515/97808047989832doi  a(DE-B1597)564248  a(OCoLC)1178769365  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aVM657b.B87 2016 4aVM657b.B874 2016 7aHIS0370602bisacsh04a387.2/0442231 aBurgess, Douglas R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEngines of Empire :bSteamships and the Victorian Imagination /cDouglas R. Burgess. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- ttable of contents -- tprologue -- tintroduction -- t1. phantasmagoria -- t2. selling the mammoth -- t3. leviathans -- t4. honor and glory crowning time -- t5. ordinary escapes -- t6. one small iron country -- t7. vandals abroad -- t8. the dollars are coming -- t9. tiffin for griffins -- t10. the floating kaiser -- t11. sitting in darkness -- tconclusion -- tnotes -- tbibliography -- tindex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1859, the S.S. Great Eastern departed from England on her maiden voyage. She was a remarkable wonder of the nineteenth century: an iron city longer than Trafalgar Square, taller than Big Ben's tower, heavier than Westminster Cathedral. Her paddles were the size of Ferris wheels; her decks could hold four thousand passengers bound for America, or ten thousand troops bound for the Raj. Yet she ended her days as a floating carnival before being unceremoniously dismantled in 1889. Steamships like the Great Eastern occupied a singular place in the Victorian mind. Crossing oceans, ferrying tourists and troops alike, they became emblems of nationalism, modernity, and humankind's triumph over the cruel elements. Throughout the nineteenth century, the spectacle of a ship's launch was one of the most recognizable symbols of British social and technological progress. Yet this celebration of the power of the empire masked overconfidence and an almost religious veneration of technology. Equating steam with civilization had catastrophic consequences for subjugated peoples around the world. Engines of Empire tells the story of the complex relationship between Victorians and their wondrous steamships, following famous travelers like Mark Twain, Charles Dickens, and Jules Verne as well as ordinary spectators, tourists, and imperial administrators as they crossed oceans bound for the colonies. Rich with anecdotes and wry humor, it is a fascinating glimpse into a world where an empire felt powerful and anything seemed possible-if there was an engine behind it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aImperialismxHistoryx19th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aPassenger shipsxHistoryx19th century. 0aPassenger shipsxHistoryy19th century. 0aSteam-navigationxHistoryx19th century. 0aSteam-navigationxHistoryy19th century. 0aSteamboatsxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aSteamboatsxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aSteamboatszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSteamboatszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aTourismxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat BritainxUnited States. 0aTourismxHistoryy19th century. 4aAtlantic. 4aBrunel. 4aSteam. 4aTwain. 4aVictorians. 4acolonial. 4aempire. 4aimperial. 4asteamships. 4atravel. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479898340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798983423C